Boil your #kettle{} and pour the boiling water (about @water{300%ml}) into a #measuring jug{}. Add the @vegetable stock powder{1/2} and stir to dissolve. Halve, peel and slice the @echalion shallot{1}(peeled and sliced into thin half moons). Halve, then remove the core from the @bell pepper{1}(halved, cored and chopped into 1cm chunks). Heat a glug of @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat. Add the shallot and pepper, stir, and cook until soft, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Stir the @tomato puree{15%g} into the veggies and cook for ~{2%minutes} more. Add the @basmati rice{150%g}, pour in the stock and bring to the boil. Lower the heat to medium and pop a #lid{} on the saucepan. Cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove from the heat and set aside (still covered) for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve.

> The rice will finish cooking in its own steam.

Meanwhile, drain the @pineapple rings{1} and chop into small ½cm chunks. Pop into a #small bowl{}. Pick the @mint{1}(leaves finely chopped, stalks discarded) from their stalks and finely chop (discard the stalks). Zest the @lime{2}(zested). Add the mint and lime zest to the pineapple along with the @olive oil{1%tbsp}(for the salsa) and a squeeze of lime juice. Set aside.

Cut the @halloumi{250}(cut into 1cm thick slices) into 1cm thick slices. Put the @olive oil{1%tbsp}(for the halloumi) in a #mixing bowl{} with the @Mexican style spice mix{1/2%tsp}. Add the halloumi to the #mixing bowl{} and carefully coat in the spice mixture. Put a #frying pan{} on high heat. Fry the halloumi slices until browned, ~{2-3%minutes} on each side. Remove from the heat.

> TIP: The Mexican spice is pretty spicy so go easy if you don't like it hot!

Roughly chop the @coriander{1/2}(roughly chopped) (stalks and all). When the rice is cooked, stir in the coriander and squeeze in some lime juice. Taste and season with @?salt{} and @?pepper{} as necessary.

Fluff up the rice, share between your plates and top with the spiced halloumi. Finish with a generous spoonful of pineapple salsa. Tuck in!